	        		        	<h1 id="firstHeading" class="firstHeading">Geneticsevolution:FossilRecord</h1>
				<div id="bodyContent">
		            <h3 id="siteSub">From Coursera</h3>
		            <div id="contentSub"></div>
		            		            		            					<!-- start content -->
					<div lang="en" dir="ltr" class="mw-content-ltr"><p>There is extensive evidence for evolution and common ancestry in the <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fossil_record">fossil record</a>. This page lists various examples of how the fossil record demonstrates that life arose from a simple single origin and diversified through the mechanics of evolution into the different species that we see on Earth today.</p>
<ul>
<li><p>The further back we go within the fossil record <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fossil#Earliest_fossiliferous_sites">the simpler the life forms</a> become.</p></li>
<li><p>Complex life forms, such as humans and rabbits, appear only much much later within the fossil record.</p></li>
<li><p>Examples (<a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Evolution_of_the_horse">like the evolution of a horse</a>) of a species gradually changing in the fossil record into new species/forms.</p></li>
<li><p>There are <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Transitional_fossils">various</a> well known "transitional fossils" that connect modern groups to their common ancestor. One of these is the <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Archaeopteryx">Archaeopteryx</a>, a transitional form of modern birds.</p></li>
</ul>

